data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives poor failure messages (just "Expected: True, Actual: False"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Specialized assertions → clear failure messages
    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Your code | Better alternative | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure says "Expected count: 3, Actual: 5" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` | Failure says "Expected non-null" |

**Other available collection assertions:**

```csharp
Assert.Contains(expectedItem, collection);
Assert.DoesNotContain(unexpectedItem, collection);
var single = Assert.ContainsSingle(collection); // exactly one element
Assert.IsEmpty(collection);
```

These all produce descriptive failure messages, making debugging much faster than a bare `Assert.IsTrue`.
